INTRODUCTION¶

Online learning has become incredibly popular lately, with big names like Google, IBM, and Meta offering a huge range of courses to help people improve their skills in areas they’re passionate about. But with so many options out there, choosing the right course can be a real challenge. Learners often spend hours trying to figure out which course is the best fit for them. On top of that, it’s tough to know which skills or courses are in demand in the job market, making it even harder for students and professionals to decide where to focus their efforts. Imagine having a tool that helps you choose the perfect course, whether you're a student trying to land your dream job or a professional looking to switch careers. A course recommendation system can do just that! By tailoring suggestions to your skills and the latest industry needs, it saves you tons of time and effort, making it easier to level up and stay ahead of the game. A good course recommendation system can also be an assistant in developing a career path.

In this project, I’ve created a complete Course Recommendation System that covers the entire Data Science lifecycle. From collecting and analyzing data to making personalized course suggestions. For instance, if a learner has finished a course and is unsure about the next step in their learning journey, this project would be perfect for guiding them in making the right choice.

Note - The Recommendation system used is a content-based filtering method, where recommendations are made based on the characteristics of the data.

Below is the high level design(HLD) flow of the Recommendation system.

Below is the complete Data Science Lifecycle flow for the Course Recommendation System.

Let’s take a closer look at each step. A detailed demonstration of each step is provided later in the document.

Step 0: The Data Source considered for this project is Coursera which is a popular online learning platform. Since Coursera is a trusted source, there are no concerns about the authenticity of the data.

Step 1: The Data is scraped using the requests and beautiful soup libraries and stored in csv file.

Step 2: After retrieving the data, the next step is to clean the data where column refactoring, handling of Null values,data type handling etc are handled in this step.

Step 3: Once the Cleaning is done, Selecting the appropriate features is one of the important steps of the entire lifecycle. Features are selected by analyzing the data and using various data visualizations to gain insights.

Step 4: Building a model based on the features selected

  • a) A model is developed using NLTK and TF-IDF techniques.
  • b) Another model is developed using Word2Vec

Step 5: Testing the Models and selecting the one that performs the best.

Step 6: Generating the Recommendations

Part 1 : DATA COLLECTION¶

The data is extracted from Coursera Website with the help of webscraping using beautifulsoup and requests library. The values extracted from the coursera Website are Course Title,Skills, Ratings,Partner,reviewsCount,level of the course, type of the course, Duration of the course. After scraping the required data, the values are stored in a CSV file. Below is a picture of the Coursera website, with the elements highlighted in red representing the parts to be scraped.

import re
import pandas as pd
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import requests

# importing the required libraries for scrapping purpose.

response = requests.get("https://www.coursera.org/courses")
html_soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

# Seperate lists for each attribute
course_title = []
course_skills = []
course_ratings = []
course_metaData = []
course_partner = []
course_reviews_count = []

def addAttributes(attributeName, tag, className,element):
    val = element.find(tag,class_=className)
    if val != None:
        attributeName.append(val.get_text(strip = True))
    else:
        attributeName.append(None)
course_title = []
course_skills = []
course_ratings = []
course_metaData = []
course_partner = []
course_reviews_count = []

for i in range(1,100):
    url = "https://www.coursera.org/courses?page=" +str(i)
    page = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(page.content, 'html.parser')
    elements = soup.find_all('div', class_='cds-ProductCard-content')

    for j in range(0,len(elements)):
        #x = elements[j].find_all('h3', class_='cds-CommonCard-title css-6ecy9b')
        addAttributes(course_title,'h3','cds-CommonCard-title css-6ecy9b',elements[j])
        addAttributes(course_metaData,'div','cds-CommonCard-metadata',elements[j])
        addAttributes(course_ratings,'div','cds-RatingStat-meter',elements[j])
        addAttributes(course_skills,'div','cds-CommonCard-bodyContent',elements[j])
        addAttributes(course_reviews_count,'div','css-vac8rf',elements[j])
        addAttributes(course_partner,'p','cds-ProductCard-partnerNames css-vac8rf',elements[j])
courses_df = pd.DataFrame({'course_title': course_title,
                          'course_organization': course_partner,
                          'course_MetaData': course_metaData,
                          'course_rating':course_ratings,
                           'course_skills':course_skills,
                           'course_reviews_count':course_reviews_count})
courses_df = courses_df.sort_values('course_title')

# here we take each lists we generated by scrapping and made a dataframe out of it is using pandas library.


courses_df.to_csv('Coursera_Courses1.csv')

def convert_reviews_count(value):
    value = str(value)
    if 'K' in value:
        # Remove 'K', convert to float, and multiply by 1000
        return float(value.replace('K', '').strip()) * 1000
    else:
        # Convert to float
        return float(value)

# Apply the function to the column
df['course_reviews_count'] = df['course_reviews_count'].apply(convert_reviews_count)

Some records have missing information about course skills. This might be because certain organizations didn’t include details about the skills a person would gain from taking the course. Additionally, some values for the features course_reviews_count and course_rating are also missing.

There are various ways to handle Null Scenarios,

  1. Can Simply remove the rows that have null value
  2. Can replace the Null value with ''.

I am opting for Approach 2 because it ensures that no data is lost. Removing an entire row from the dataset just because one feature has a missing value is not ideal. The other features in that row, which do have valid values, can still provide valuable information and make meaningful contributions to the recommendation system.

Part 4: MODEL IMPLEMENTATION¶

NLP - Using NLTK

Approach 1: TF-IDF

The below is the flow chart of TF-IDF approach. All the features are combined in one column and that particular column is passed to word_tokenizer which is an inbuilt function in NLTK module used to convert the corpus into Tokens. These Tokens are then passed to the Stemmer which performs the stemming of the tokens. Then this stemmed output is passed to the TF-IDF Vectorizer which would convert the textal data to numerical representations. This represents the importance of a word in a document relative to a collection of documents. After the vectors are created, the cosine similarity is computed for input vector and all the vectors in the dataset. The top 7 recommendations are determined by selecting the 7 highest Cosine Similarity values.

stemmer = PorterStemmer()

def token(t):
    token = nltk.word_tokenize(t)
    w = [stemmer.stem(w) for w in token]
    return " ".join(w)

def recommender(name):
    # Get the index of the course with the given title
    idx = df[df['course_title'] == name].index[0]

    # Ensure the matrix is dense
    global matrix
    if not isinstance(matrix, np.ndarray):
        matrix = matrix.toarray()

    # Cosine Similarity
    cosine_sim = cosine_similarity(matrix)
    
    # Manhattan (L1) and Euclidean (L2) Distances
    manhattan_distances = np.sum(np.abs(matrix - matrix[idx, :]), axis=1)
    euclidean_distances = np.linalg.norm(matrix - matrix[idx, :], axis=1)

    # Compute and sort the cosine similarity in descending order
    distances = sorted(list(enumerate(cosine_sim[idx])), reverse=True, key=lambda x: x[1])
    
    # Initialize the result list
    coursesList = []
    
    # Iterate over the top recommendations (excluding the course itself at index 0)
    for n_id in distances[1:8]:
        course_title = df.iloc[n_id[0]].course_title
        cosine_similarity_value = n_id[1]
        manhattan_distance = manhattan_distances[n_id[0]]
        euclidean_distance = euclidean_distances[n_id[0]]
        
        # Append results with all metrics
        coursesList.append({
            'course_title': course_title,
            'cosine_similarity': cosine_similarity_value,
            'manhattan_distance': manhattan_distance,
            'euclidean_distance': euclidean_distance,
        })

    return coursesList

# Call the function
recommendations = recommender('Big Data')
for rec in recommendations:
    print(rec)

Visualizaing the Word Embeddings

Note - For better visualization, a subset of the dataframe is considered.

The flow chart below shows how word embeddings are generated.

As mentioned earlier, a sample dataset is used after applying TF-IDF vectorization to make the data easier to visualize. Then, Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is applied to reduce the multi-dimensional data down to two dimensions. This makes it simpler to visualize and analyze the data in a more manageable space. After that, K-means clustering is used on the reduced data to group similar courses together into different clusters.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Assuming 'df' is the original dataset with a 'features_combined' column
# Compute TF-IDF for the entire dataset
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
tfidf_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(df['featuresCombined'])

# Take a sample of 20 rows for demonstration
df_sampled = df.sample(n=20, random_state=6).reset_index(drop=True)
tfidf_sampled = vectorizer.transform(df_sampled['featuresCombined'])

# Apply PCA to reduce dimensions to 2D for visualization
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
reduced_embeddings = pca.fit_transform(tfidf_sampled.toarray())

# Apply KMeans clustering
n_clusters = 5
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=42)
labels = kmeans.fit_predict(reduced_embeddings)

# Plot the embeddings and clusters
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Initialize a dictionary to store course titles for each cluster
cluster_courses = {i: [] for i in range(n_clusters)}

# Plot data points with cluster colors
for i in range(n_clusters):
    cluster_points = reduced_embeddings[labels == i]
    plt.scatter(cluster_points[:, 0], cluster_points[:, 1], label=f"Cluster {i}")

    # Collect course titles for the legend
    cluster_courses[i] = df_sampled['course_title'][labels == i].tolist()

# Add cluster centers
for i, center in enumerate(kmeans.cluster_centers_):
    plt.scatter(center[0], center[1], marker='x', s=200, color='black', label=f"Center {i}")
    plt.text(center[0], center[1], f"Center {i}", fontsize=10, color='black', ha='center', va='center')

# Annotate individual course titles
for i, title in enumerate(df_sampled['course_title']):
    x, y = reduced_embeddings[i]
    plt.text(x + 0.02, y + 0.02, title, fontsize=9)

# Create a legend with courses listed under each cluster
legend_labels = []
for i in range(n_clusters):
    cluster_label = f"Cluster {i}:\n" + "\n".join(cluster_courses[i])
    legend_labels.append((plt.Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', markerfacecolor=plt.cm.tab10(i), markersize=10), cluster_label))

# Add the legend outside the plot
plt.legend(*zip(*legend_labels), loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), fontsize=8)

# Final plot settings
plt.title("2D Visualization of Course Title Embeddings with KMeans Clustering")
plt.xlabel("PCA Component 1")
plt.ylabel("PCA Component 2")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The graph above shows word embeddings after applying PCA and K-means clustering, where similar words are grouped into clusters. For example, courses shown in red are related to marketing, including Think Outside the Inbox: Email Marketing, and Google SEO Fundamentals. Courses related to Data Science are shown in green, such as Data Analysis with R Programming and Applied Data Science with R. Similarly, system administration courses are in blue, and courses related to game design, UX design, and other software technologies are shown in purple. This visualization makes it easier to understand the word embeddings.

Approach 2: Word2Vec

The below is the flow chart of Word2Vec approach. All the features are combined in one column and that particular column is passed to word_tokenizer which is an inbuilt function in NLTK module used to convert the corpus into Tokens. This tokenized output is passed to the Word2Vec which captures the semantic relationships between words. After the vectors are created, the cosine similarity is computed for input vector and all the vectors in the dataset. The top 7 recommendations are determined by selecting the 7 highest Cosine Similarity values.

In [ ]:
import numpy as np
from scipy.spatial.distance import cosine

df['tokenized_features'] = df['featuresCombined'].apply(lambda x: word_tokenize(x.lower()))

# Step 2: Train the Word2Vec model
model = Word2Vec(
    sentences=df['tokenized_features'].tolist(),  # Tokenized sentences
    vector_size=100,  # Size of word vectors
    window=5,  # Context window size
    min_count=1,  # Minimum word frequency
    sg=0  # Use CBOW (0) or Skip-gram (1)
)

def euclidean_distance(vector1, vector2):
    return np.linalg.norm(vector1 - vector2)

def manhattan_distance(vector1, vector2):
    return np.sum(np.abs(vector1 - vector2))

def recommend_courses(course_title, df, model, top_n=8):
    
    input_tokens = df[df['course_title'] == course_title]['tokenized_features'].values[0]

    # Compute input vector (filter out-of-vocabulary tokens)
    valid_input_tokens = [token for token in input_tokens if token in model.wv.key_to_index]
    input_vector = model.wv.get_mean_vector(valid_input_tokens, pre_normalize=True, post_normalize=True)

    # Calculate similarities for all courses
    similarities = []
    for i, row in df.iterrows():
        valid_course_tokens = [token for token in row['tokenized_features'] if token in model.wv.key_to_index]
        course_vector = model.wv.get_mean_vector(valid_course_tokens, pre_normalize=True, post_normalize=True)

        # Cosine Similarity
        cosine_sim = 1 - cosine(input_vector, course_vector)

        # Euclidean Distance
        euclidean_dist = euclidean_distance(input_vector, course_vector)

        # Manhattan Distance
        manhattan_dist = manhattan_distance(input_vector, course_vector)


        # Append the similarity measures with descriptive keys
        similarities.append({
            'course_title': row['course_title'],
            'cosine_similarity': cosine_sim,
            'euclidean_distance': euclidean_dist,
            'manhattan_distance': manhattan_dist,
        })

    # Sort by Cosine Similarity and return top_n recommendations
    similarities_sorted = sorted(similarities, key=lambda x: x['cosine_similarity'], reverse=True)  # Sorting by cosine similarity
    return similarities_sorted[1:top_n]

Part 5: MODEL ANALYSIS¶

Comparing the Output of both the Models => (TF-IDF) and (Word2Vec)

  1. Cosine Similarity

import plotly.graph_objects as go

def compareCosineSimilarities(tcmodel1, tcmodel2, testCase):
    # Create the figure
    fig = go.Figure()

    # Add Model 1 data with distinct markers for legend
    for item in tcmodel1:
        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
            x=[item['cosine_similarity']],
            y=['Model 1'],
            mode='markers',
            marker=dict(symbol='x', size=10, color='blue'),
            text=[f"Course: {item['course_title']}<br>Cosine Similarity: {item['cosine_similarity']}"],  # Hover text
            hoverinfo='text',
            name=f"Model 1 - {item['course_title']}<br>Cosine Similarity: {item['cosine_similarity']:.7f}"  # Course title and Cosine Similarity in the legend
        ))

    # Add Model 2 data with distinct markers for legend
    for item in tcmodel2:
        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
            x=[item['cosine_similarity']],
            y=['Model 2'],
            mode='markers',
            marker=dict(symbol='circle', size=10, color='red'),
            text=[f"Course: {item['course_title']}<br>Cosine Similarity: {item['cosine_similarity']}"],  # Hover text
            hoverinfo='text',
            name=f"Model 2 - {item['course_title']}<br>Cosine Similarity: {item['cosine_similarity']:.7f}"  # Course title and Cosine Similarity in the legend
        ))

    # Customize layout
    fig.update_layout(
        title=f'Cosine Similarity Comparison (Model 1 vs Model 2) For Test Case {testCase}',
        xaxis_title='Cosine Similarity',
        yaxis_title='Model',
        yaxis=dict(categoryorder='category ascending'),  # Order categories on y-axis
        legend_title='Models and Courses',
        hovermode='closest',
        xaxis=dict(
            tickmode='linear',
            tick0=0.7,
            dtick=0.05  # Define the tick step
        )
    )

    # Show the plot
    fig.show()

In general, cosine similarity is a reliable metric for measuring the similarity between vectors, and it works well with both TF-IDF and Word2Vec. However, since Word2Vec tends to produce values close to 1, it's a good idea to consider other similarity metrics as well to capture more variation among the data points and determine which model performs better.

  1. Euclidean Distance and Manhatten Distance

import plotly.graph_objects as go

def compareDistances(tcmodel1, tcmodel2, testCase):
    # Create the figure
    fig = go.Figure()

    # Add Model 1 data for Manhattan Distance
    for item in tcmodel1:
        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
            x=[item['manhattan_distance']],
            y=['Manhattan Distance'],
            mode='markers',
            marker=dict(symbol='x', size=10, color='blue'),
            text=[f"Course: {item['course_title']}<br>Manhattan Distance: {item['manhattan_distance']}"],  # Hover text
            hoverinfo='text',
            name=f"Model 1 - {item['course_title']}<br>Manhattan Distance: {item['manhattan_distance']:.7f}"  # Course title and Manhattan Distance in the legend
        ))

    # Add Model 2 data for Manhattan Distance
    for item in tcmodel2:
        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
            x=[item['manhattan_distance']],
            y=['Manhattan Distance'],
            mode='markers',
            marker=dict(symbol='circle', size=10, color='red'),
            text=[f"Course: {item['course_title']}<br>Manhattan Distance: {item['manhattan_distance']}"],  # Hover text
            hoverinfo='text',
            name=f"Model 2 - {item['course_title']}<br>Manhattan Distance: {item['manhattan_distance']:.7f}"  # Course title and Manhattan Distance in the legend
        ))

    # Add Model 1 data for Euclidean Distance
    for item in tcmodel1:
        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
            x=[item['euclidean_distance']],
            y=['Euclidean Distance'],
            mode='markers',
            marker=dict(symbol='x', size=10, color='blue'),
            text=[f"Course: {item['course_title']}<br>Euclidean Distance: {item['euclidean_distance']}"],  # Hover text
            hoverinfo='text',
            name=f"Model 1 - {item['course_title']}<br>Euclidean Distance: {item['euclidean_distance']:.7f}"  # Course title and Euclidean Distance in the legend
        ))

    # Add Model 2 data for Euclidean Distance
    for item in tcmodel2:
        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(
            x=[item['euclidean_distance']],
            y=['Euclidean Distance'],
            mode='markers',
            marker=dict(symbol='circle', size=10, color='red'),
            text=[f"Course: {item['course_title']}<br>Euclidean Distance: {item['euclidean_distance']}"],  # Hover text
            hoverinfo='text',
            name=f"Model 2 - {item['course_title']}<br>Euclidean Distance: {item['euclidean_distance']:.7f}"  # Course title and Euclidean Distance in the legend
        ))

    # Customize layout
    fig.update_layout(
        title=f'Distance Metric Comparison (Manhattan vs Euclidean) For Test Case {testCase}',
        xaxis_title='Distance Value',
        yaxis_title='Distance Metric',
        yaxis=dict(
            categoryorder='category ascending',  # Order categories on y-axis
            tickmode='array',  # Use an array for custom labels
            tickvals=['Manhattan Distance', 'Euclidean Distance'],
            ticktext=['Manhattan', 'Euclidean']
        ),
        legend_title='Models and Courses with Distances',
        hovermode='closest',
        xaxis=dict(
            tickmode='linear',
            tick0=0.0,
            dtick=0.05,  # Define the tick step
            tickangle=45  # Rotate x-axis ticks to prevent overlap
        ),
        showlegend=True
    )

    # Show the plot
    fig.show()

Description of the plots - The above plots are a depiction of comparison of Euclidean Distances and Manhattan distances for all the test cases which are introduced earlier as part of this project. The red dots('o') represent model2 and the blue crosses('X') represent model 1. The y-axis represents type of Distance Metric and the x-axis represents the distance values.

Note - If the distance is less, it indicates that the vectors are similar.

Insights from the plot:

  1. For both distance metrics, Model 2 has much smaller distance values than Model 1, which makes sense because Word2Vec looks at the meaning of the words, while TF-IDF focuses on the structure of the words. However, in test case 5, there is one course where Model 1 has a smaller distance value than Model 2. This shows that in some rare cases, the structure of the words might be more important than their meaning.
  2. The Euclidean distance values for both models are smaller compared to the Manhattan distance, which is expected because Manhattan distance uses the absolute value of the differences, while Euclidean distance takes the square root of the squared differences. The graph also illustrates this difference.
  3. The distance metrics capture some variance in the points, which is reflected in the graph, providing a clearer visualization and better understanding of the models' performance across the test cases.

Part 6: CONCLUSION¶

This is the final part of the entire Data Science life cycle. In this section we will be making conclusions based on the Analysis we have done.

  • With the help of the Word Clouds which we have generated in Part 3 Section we can infer that most popular courses in the industry currently are Data Analysis, Machine learning and Computer Programming. (This inference is made only based on Coursera dataset)
  • Majority of the courses are offered by leading tech industries like IBM,Google and Microsoft.
  • Another interesting insight is that most of the courses published on Coursera are beginner-friendly, encouraging learners to start building a skill.
  • TF-IDF vectorization is a syntactic approach where the relationship between the words is not captured while Word2Vec is a symantic approach where the words that occur in similar context have similar embeddings. Hence, the similarity values for Word2Vec model are higher than the other.
  • The above point is confirmed by comparing the cosine similarity and distance metrics (Euclidean and Manhattan) for both models. From the plots, it’s clear that the similarity values are much higher for Model 2 (Word2Vec) compared to Model 1 (TF-IDF).
